TextBlock.TextLine: In Antwerp 15 aprill 1681
London Aptlur Anneslay
S. my last to you was on the 29: pass with a remise for £94:16:3 on m
remainin shute, thought sece non from you yett, hope you have well
Reccauld itt & that itt is accepted & will be payd in due time I have some
mony more for yd acctt. which my next will bring you in a bill this beeng
cheebly for advise, that thomas Elsdon from exon is well arrived att brugs
on his board a bale I.M.N2 with ul white perpetuanos from mr. Ledging hom
of which he sent mee the inclosed invoyce & hath drawne £40 on you
which & the rest pleale to pay him I finde also a balo A.A N. 6 shipped
to yd order, whether that must go for Lille or this please, I know not so
exspected yd advise & remaine In Antwarp 15 Aprill 1681
London hel Scawen
S. I have before mee yd of I curitt as for the lace trade, I have sent the very some
sorts & prijses, as I uso to provide for others, so that I did exspect N.1 would
prove to content, and that you should have or dispose as well of these sorts
as others, do whoever, seeng I have now yd in structions, shall make up the
pack formerly mentioned accordingly & what faults you finde shall be rectifn
with all care mayinable, & I doubt not, butt you will finde my buyingto
content, I wonder my goods should prove deares then those of in sabeiton
where as I have formerly tryed with him & others, butt my freund did
al wayes complaine of what he bought, so that sence I made itt mj buysyne
have hadd no more complaintes whoever I am ready to leane & to do
better for the future, if possible which I hape the next parquet will shep
whilst proimtrim payd faile not to dispose of what alreayd g sent as
best you can before any of what is send goeth out of fushion & rather
loose att first, then att last. I have given you cred itt for my ½ part in
255 p callicres shipt observing that 5 bales browne longh cloth are
shipt aboard Adriain Deraer, seeng you do not pack them in cottons. &
wonder you did not send y with muchall deraes, for he 1s sailed & as Iam
told arrived & Adriaen hath an old ship, & gott a lake last time
pray advise mee how the dungares are packt to declare them according
suposing that the pack M„N.11 from mr. maynard doth containe the
106 p salempores, muliius & to undernoted mys invoye god send all
fase over: sence the hollands casin die comp. sild their goods, is brough
such a quantitie hether that I doubt mee shall not be able to advance
up on the goods that must pay iustume of which the experency dothrearh
us for I have still in sold the last 3 bales & all the rest is sold exceptta
fine of pN4 of 47 st so finde that what must pay the duties that
takes awaij the gaine I want most dyed goods, haveing non ankn
therefore disparch the rest with all speed & divert our risico as for merly
desired when all is don I loo up on ghe salempores to be the sort that
wee mustkeep on, for the fcture for them I finde accommoyable to
every one & what pays custome renders no proffitt in case m. maynar
hath no cettons enough, lett him buy more, that so there be not to many
in one bale, butt made up as directed, of which exspecting yd advise
remaine with kinde salues
In Antwerp 15 aprill 81
London Ahram vivvans
th
my last to you was on the 12 curitt to which please to be referre in all
ber theusars. sence recd. yd of p curitt as for the buring of bayes lett
y. do their ut most to have the best sorts for their prijses which prjses
on &mitt as I have noted to you, & give a good clarges to bay
hose hat save no less then of ayd broad and ayd, thich & well couered
will & not so thin & slight as many in the last parcell kan
dhae ake is ie good sort of 37 a 31t & I6 of those I have sold
great quantitus wee estined also the. I.R, butt the last you sent wercso
slight asever I saw 16.S. is also a good marck a governo - as to alderman
samuel sijkes, can you gett in with him leave the others, or att least
lett him make atryall of all sorts, for he understands the bussynes to
my know ledge & experiency, where fore I would rather have you to in order
att least some goods from him for he is able to do itt well & as cheapes
any other what soever: I have tole you that the cloathes sent do not hold
out their lenght nor brath where fore there must be punctually
notice taken that they befulls t yd white with in the lifts, short
in their wooll drest & prest all the cloth over & not onely about the lifts
where they are seen, for other wise wee have no soones complaints, butt
when the goods are opened, so pleased to considder that all our gaine depend
from well buying in, God be thanked wee hadd a good sale & do not question
butt you will finde the proffitt answerable & really, had imr. chipping
been adving wee should have advanced yett more, because I onely soed most
of the last goods for want of others, butt itt is not to gett reputation
bij where fore wee must have a fast hand againd that doth itt well over
elce wre are undon & I kent is so well sereed, that he hath hetherto
eexceeded us I must advise you not to be intimate with him, for he
will not freind you butt onely gett his advantidge by yd discours & so
In Antwarp: 15 Aprill
London Henry Maynard
pmso
S. I have before mee yd of p. curitt as yett have no news of any goods arrived att
Rotterdam, af sooneas they are aver shall on order more which I delayd,
because exspect some now pattarnes everj day, which shall be sent you ms
not wonder that I do not in ordere goorse st with all speed to governe yd
self accordingly you must not wonder that I do not ip order 40 or 50 spanis
cloathes att time first our demand is slow, besides I utt off non or few
except I gett a fair better ratt then formerly & goods so much deaver keeps
every one backward in buying, I want almost allsorts of cullours in low
prijses from 6 to 7 s ayd butt no grayes more, of which you will have a
more complg instructions pr. next dispatch the blews & auroras with all
speed, for they are much wanted I wonder I receaved no pattarnes from you
of the bale of Posins in ordered from the north neither any advise that is
don with them I could wish them here, for I have not one p resting of what
sort, so pacy do not for gett itt & to wards the latter end of next month
will be time to provided white kersies, where fore you may gett a bald of
1½ lenght made towards that time, butt they must be of al most 3 ½quart
of ayd broadred lifts for unless they hold out an elland ½ quarter that is thse
wee can not sell y. where fore itt would be the better, in case they were ⅓ of
ayd full broad, aa governo. I long to see the northen cloathes, for I shall
want more towards summer & would faine see these goods first, before
wee proceed I have given you creditt for my Lpart in the bale N. 11 withree
cottons, which I supose come to late togo michiel Dehaes, because some
body told mee that he is ready arrived, so do exspect to heare further as to
that as also of the shipping of, of the resting cottons & the acctt of
sale of last month is made up butt for want of time not drawne outso
shall send itt p next without faile, shall also very speedly remitt you for
boath acctt. beeng a gathering for that purpose whilst I remaine
mr. maynard I want here apress to make packes such as yd packersuso
to make up their packes wherefore could wish you would provide one of the
longest sorted because our roomes are deepter then yd in England, whoenes as
best you can have itt I should gett one made here butt ous peaile donsr undessard
itt eacept ittwere a great heauy thing to pres cloathes & that I want not onely
to make packes when occasion regueres, so you mist gett itt with all the needfull
as cheip as you can provide itt
